00:28:58.820 --> 00:29:01.240
as a rumor, not, like,
a confirmed fact.

00:29:01.240 --> 00:29:03.490
So I was wondering what do
you have to say about that,

00:29:03.490 --> 00:29:06.097
and whether the movie addresses
the issue at all or not.

00:29:06.097 --> 00:29:06.930
SHIRIN NESHAT: Yeah.

00:29:06.930 --> 00:29:09.160
I mean, I'm really
glad you brought

00:29:09.160 --> 00:29:12.460
that up because first
of all, every Egyptian

00:29:12.460 --> 00:29:18.760
you speak to has a different
explanation or impression

00:29:18.760 --> 00:29:21.370
and relationship to Oum Kulthum.

00:29:21.370 --> 00:29:24.670
So what I found, also, about
her sexual orientation,

00:29:24.670 --> 00:29:26.570
everyone said
something different.

00:29:26.570 --> 00:29:30.730
Some people say she absolutely
was in love with so-and-so.

00:29:30.730 --> 00:29:33.910
But she did eventually
marry her doctor.

00:29:33.910 --> 00:29:37.390
At the end, when she died,
she was married to him.

00:29:37.390 --> 00:29:40.510
And she adopted a son.

00:29:40.510 --> 00:29:43.600
And many people say
that she was absolutely

00:29:43.600 --> 00:29:45.940
working with men, but
in love with woman.

00:29:45.940 --> 00:29:50.790
And at the beginning we did
a lot of research about that.

00:29:50.790 --> 00:29:57.160
And we, indeed, there was a lot
of images and videos of her,

00:29:57.160 --> 00:30:00.670
really, the time that she
laughed a lot and seemed--

00:30:00.670 --> 00:30:03.190
because when she was performing,
she was always very rigid.

00:30:03.190 --> 00:30:06.790
The time that she was seem
most relaxed was around woman,

00:30:06.790 --> 00:30:08.000
you know.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.032
It seemed like she
really felt comfortable.

00:30:10.032 --> 00:30:11.740
Of course, it happens
for a lot of woman,

00:30:11.740 --> 00:30:14.080
just even if you're not gay.

00:30:14.080 --> 00:30:16.900
But I think everything
hinted at the fact

00:30:16.900 --> 00:30:20.069
that for her conservative
environment that she lived,

00:30:20.069 --> 00:30:21.610
it was absolutely
out of the question

00:30:21.610 --> 00:30:24.100
that she could be open about it.

00:30:24.100 --> 00:30:27.610
But also the Egyptians
didn't really wanted

00:30:27.610 --> 00:30:31.130
to devour her personal
life in that way,

00:30:31.130 --> 00:30:33.090
like the way we do
with celebrities here,

00:30:33.090 --> 00:30:35.440
which I really respected.

00:30:35.440 --> 00:30:39.010
Some people I talked to
said, it didn't matter to us.

00:30:39.010 --> 00:30:40.870
Some people said,
oh, no, she was not.

00:30:40.870 --> 00:30:42.830
And some people
say, yes, she was.

00:30:42.830 --> 00:30:47.750
But in general, I find that
the status that she reached,

00:30:47.750 --> 00:30:50.740
it's wildly different.

00:30:50.740 --> 00:30:53.800
You have Michael Jackson
here, I mean, his sexuality--

00:30:53.800 --> 00:30:58.510
like, the biggest American
icon as a pop artist.

00:30:58.510 --> 00:31:01.360
But you understand
that he really

00:31:01.360 --> 00:31:05.110
was devoured, in the way,
for his celebrity status.

00:31:05.110 --> 00:31:08.770
But Oum Kulthum, they
just loved her music.

00:31:08.770 --> 00:31:13.420
And it didn't matter if she was
a woman or a man or gay or not.

00:31:13.420 --> 00:31:16.690
And that's what I admired
about her and her relationship

00:31:16.690 --> 00:31:20.770
to her audience, that they
didn't destroy her like the way

00:31:20.770 --> 00:31:21.370
we do.

00:31:21.370 --> 00:31:25.930
You know, Amy Winehouse,
Whitney Houston, Edith Piaf,

00:31:25.930 --> 00:31:27.700
Billie Holiday.

00:31:27.700 --> 00:31:29.530
Every great artist
that we build up,

00:31:29.530 --> 00:31:33.970
we bring down because we
just-- oh, she was very freaky.

00:31:33.970 --> 00:31:38.260
But in reality, like I said,
I've found that she has this

00:31:38.260 --> 00:31:43.860
very sacred place that you
just cannot take away from her.

00:31:43.860 --> 00:31:47.230
And people were really
the most religious,

00:31:47.230 --> 00:31:50.110
conservative community
just left her alone

00:31:50.110 --> 00:31:52.020
because they loved her.

00:31:52.020 --> 00:31:55.130
And I think that's so rare.

00:31:55.130 --> 00:31:58.030
And it honestly is something
I took a lot of pride

00:31:58.030 --> 00:32:01.900
that we in the Middle
East have an artist

00:32:01.900 --> 00:32:04.010
in that level of
popularity where

00:32:04.010 --> 00:32:06.000
four million people went--

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:07.780
it was one of the
largest funerals

00:32:07.780 --> 00:32:11.770
ever in the history of
Egypt, after Nasser, I think.

00:32:11.770 --> 00:32:14.440
In America, in the West,
you have never, ever

00:32:14.440 --> 00:32:18.130
seen this many people go for,
even for Michael Jackson,

00:32:18.130 --> 00:32:19.180
to a funeral.

00:32:19.180 --> 00:32:22.030
The artist just
never that popular.

00:32:22.030 --> 00:32:29.006
And in a way, it didn't
matter her sexuality so much.

